​Anxiety in the Time of COVID-19

Dealing with the COVID-19 pandemic has been stressful for everyone. For many individuals who have anxiety (and depression), it has been nearly unbearable. 

In this month’s article we will talk about anxiety—how you might feel if you have anxiety and what you can do to manage mild anxiety. 

To read this month's article, please visit: http://www.bethellutheran.org/anxiety-in-the-time-of-covid-19/

node.text: Oh great news because there isnt a place for rent in this whole fkn state for 1200$

@veganbeastmode bro im in need myself and on unemployment. It's real shit. I think mainly bc they are way overwhelmed, most are just getting approved and it's all automated. Trust me lot of people that didn't need it were making bank. They need to change the way they give this out so it only goes to people in need. For example let's say you make $12/hr working 30hrs a week and get cut bc covid. Someone else is making $45/hr and gets their hours REDUCED, not completely let go. They will qualify for a higher, most likely max unemployment benefits because the amount that they are affected for is greater than the amount you're affected by. That's what happened with one friend I know. The more you make, the more you get from unemployment. And no regulation, they don't ask how much your rent and expenses are and they don't even check if you still live in Los Angeles or California.

@pennyscrooge I’ve maxed out on unemployment before... even with Covid, you’re still not making “bank.” If your hours are reduced, you can only claim those hours lost, not more than that. So if your making $45 an hour, you’re still hitting a cap that is nowhere near that $45. You’re making closer to $15.

@veganbeastmode bro im telling you. My friend got his hours reduced from 40 to 30 getting paid $45/hr and they maxed him out. $450 + the weekly $600. $45 x 10hrs lost is exactly $450 which is what he got. But his rent was hella cheap and he was still getting paid those 30hrs, plus the additional $600 on top of it is what made it "bank". The reason we ran out of that money so damn quick is because it went to a lot of people that honestly didn't need it. Sure a ton of people that needed it too, but there was zero control aside from automated system comparing numbers.

They need to raise it and only give it to low income people. I know plenty of people that collected big unemployment and stimulus money while getting paid a ton at their job still or even while not living in Cali anymore. Honestly needs more control so we don't run out of funds so quickly

node.text:
Day 166 of #lifeduringapandemic 

This is the evening view from my porch. Such gratitude for being able to live in this beautiful place. 

Gratitude as well for the last several years that I've spent in therapy since leaving my marriage of almost 20 years. I'm reminded regularly that learning to be healthy is work. Establishing healthy boundaries and expectations is hard work. The downside of getting married at 18 and again at 24, is that I've had to learn and work at being in relationship with others as an adult. Both romantically and platonically, as well as learning to be in relationship with myself. Which has been the hardest. Our culture doesn't do a great job at preparing us to be comfortable with ourselves. 

I was just chatting with a pal, and it hit me that I've become quite comfortable with myself in a way that I never could have imagined. 

Turns out that tending to our emotional, mental and spiritual well being is the most important #Selfcare that we can engage in. It's not as sexy as a good pedicure, massage or retail therapy, but tending to our essential well being is what grounds us for the trials of life. 

Having that revelation, while taking in this view is indeed a gift. #grownladyshit #growingup #midlifemusings #middleage #healing #healthychanges #soulwork #coviving #pandemic #pandemicmusings #lifeduringcovid19 #coronavirusdiarys #maineislandlife #maineislands #bgimchronicles #blackwomenwellness #mentalhealth

This face is a pretty good representation of not only motherhood, but how I feel about returning to school next week.

I will be doing a mixture of telehealth sessions and in person sessions. I want this virus to be over already. I want to be back in school full-time without the stress of scheduling all these different kids in person or on video.

I miss being social with the schools I serve without a mask. I love smiling and to see others smile. I'm sick of video sessions. Let's just say I have such mixed feelings about returning to school. I'm happy, sad, anxious, angry etc. 

I've learned something today. We need to embrace the chaos because it makes us better people. I'm so stressed and uncertain what my job will look like day to day, but I do know I love helping kids and being apart of these schools. So I will be there to support them and help the kids during this difficult time. 

WE ARE IN THIS TOGETHER!

node.text:
Racial violence, a pandemic, a hurricane – we are being inundated with fear triggers. To make matters worse, some politicians think it useful to stoke our fears.
 
Fear is powerful. It works deep in the brain, in a part that dates back to our reptilian ancestors. It is meant to help us survive by helping us fight or flee. Yet today, we fear many things we can’t literally fight or flee.
 
Fear constricts our thinking and narrows our focus. We tend to lose our perception of anything except our fear. Perhaps the best example – and metaphor – is sight. Fear focuses us tightly on what is in the center of our field of vision. We ignore the peripheral stuff.
 
When we face immediate danger, this focus is useful for survival. But if we get stuck here, there are problems. For most of life, we need to keep perception open. Without peripheral perception, we have difficulty experiencing peace, love, creativity, intuition – the qualities we cultivate in spirituality.
 
When fear is triggered, what can we do to open our perception?
 
1. Recognize fear in our bodies. We can cultivate awareness through mindfulness.
2. Sit with the feeling without trying to flee from it. Gently investigate it. But if fear becomes overwhelming, it’s fine to distract ourselves for a while.
3. Take appropriate action. The energy of fear seeks physical release. Sometimes there are things we can do: vote, give, volunteer, protest. Often, though, there is no immediate physical action we can take. Aerobic exercise or mindful movement can offer a surrogate physical release.
4. Accept what we cannot change. This may require ongoing meditation, prayer or a similar spiritual practice.
 
“Perfect love casts out fear,” says the Bible (1 Jn 4.18). This is true at a neurological level. We let go of fear as we expand our awareness to take in more of the whole – to care for others, to snuggle a pet, to tend the soil.
 
So, take care of your emotions. Stay mindful of the messages you receive from media and politics. Keep yourself in love as much as you can. We need peace and creativity to face the very real problems before us.
 
~~~
 
üì∏ M. T. ElGassier (Unsplash).

During one hurricane briefing at the White House, Trump said, "I got it. I got it. Why don't we nuke them?" according to one source who was there. "They start forming off the coast of Africa, as they're moving across the Atlantic, we drop a bomb inside the eye of the hurricane and it disrupts it. The briefer "was knocked back on his heels," the source in the room added. "You could hear a gnat fart in that meeting. People were astonished. After the meeting ended, we thought, 'What the f---? What do we do with this?'"
Trump also raised the idea in another conversation with a senior administration official. A 2017 NSC memo describes that second conversation, in which Trump asked whether the administration should bomb hurricanes to stop them from hitting the homeland.¬†

node.text:
Subhanallah, Inilah Mukjizat Alquran Tentang Sungai di Dasar Laut

Suatu hari, seorang ahli kelautan bernama Jacques Yves Costeau melakukan penelitian di dasar laut untuk Discovery Channel. Ia menelurusi fenomena bawah laut di Cenota Angelita, Mexico.

Saat melakukan penyelaman, ia dikejutkan dengan sebuah fenomena alam yang luar biasa. Dia menemukan air tawar di antara air laut yang asin. Penemuan itu membuatnya takjub.¬† Bagaimana mungkin air tawar bisa berada terpisah dalam air laut yang asin? Tetapi itulah kenyataan yang dia temukan di dalam laut.

Rasa ingin tahunya yang besar membuat Costeau kembali menyelam lebih dalam lagi. Ia menyaksikan fenomena alam yang lebih mengejutkan lagi. Betapa tidak. Ia melihat ada sungai di dasar lautan.

Sungai di bawah laut itu ditumbuhi daun-daunan dan pohon. Para peneliti menyebut fenomena itu sebagai lapisan Hidrogen Sulfida. Tapi tampak seperti sungai? Yang menjadi tanda tanya par ahli, mengapa air yang mengalir di sungai bawah laut itu rasanya tawar?

Sesungguhnya, sekitar 14 abad lalu, Alquran telah menjelaskan fenomena itu.¬† Simak saja surah Al-Furqan [25] ayat 53: ''Dan Dialah yang membiarkan dua laut mengalir (berdampingan); yang ini tawar dan segar dan yang lain sangat asin lagi pahit; dan Dia Jadikan antara keduanya dinding dan barat yang tidak tembus.''
